nues to make an essential contribution to Deleuze scholarship today, and this new translation is set to become an event within Deleuze Studies for many years to come.Distinguishes Deleuze’s notion of the event from the phenomenological, ontological and voluntarist conceptions that continue to lay claim to it todayWith an introduction by Gregg Lambert and Daniel W. Smith, two of the world's leading commentators on Deleuze, explaining the key themes and arguments of Zourabichvili's work  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2022) 0aPhilosophy, Frenchx20th century. 0aPhilosophy, Frenchy20th century. 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aAarons, Kieran, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLambert, Gregg, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aLambert, Gregg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Daniel W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSmith, Daniel W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZourabichvili, François, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311078046840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748645633423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748645633/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK